abstract: FIRE IN BROOKLYN.--Friday night last a four-story brick building at the corner of Warren and Nevins streets took fire, and was soon consumed. The frame buildings adjoining, on Warren-street, were partially consumed. The brick house was owned by Mrs. FARRELL--loss $3,000. It was occupied by a number of families, and a corner as a barroom. Nearly everything was destroyed. Loss $1,000. No insurance. The frame buildings were owned by WM. A. COIT. LOSS $1,000. Insured.

abstract: To the Editor of the New-York Times: Your Havana correspondent speaks of a difference having occurred between Commodore PAULDING and the Consul-General at Havana. abstract: ROBBERY IN THE PARK BANK.-On Monday last $115 in bills were stolen from the Cashier's desk of the Park Bank in Beekman-street. Captain WEED, of the Second Precinct, was informed of the robbery, and officer MICHAELS was instructed to investigate the affair. This officer made diligent inquiries, but could only learn that three little boys had been seen loitering about the Bank on the afternoon of the robbery.

abstract: Mr. DOUGLAS spoke this evening three hours to an overcrowded audience. He first reviewed his own course on the Slavery question, since 1843, to show not be had acquiesced in the Missouri Compromise until the principle of popular sovereignty was introduced, when he embraced it, and afterwards applied t to Kansas. All he asked now was that it should be fairly carried out,--and this, he went on to show, the Lecompton Constitution did not do.
